HFAJuly 29, 2015  
Startup Uses Novel Vehicle for Liquid Alts
An alumnus of mutual-fund manager Equinox Funds has started a business that will develop alternative-investment vehicles structured as unit investment trusts.Michel Serieyssol, who spent four years as a sales executive at Equinox, is operating under the banner Olden Lane from an office in Princeton, N.J. He is planning a variety of offerings aimed primarily at retail investors.First up is a unit investment trust dubbed Olden Lane Outcome Series Capped Performance Portfolio with Contingent Protection, designed for investors who want to hedge against a correction in the S&P 500 Index while capturing market gains. Unit investment trusts are closed-end vehicles that maintain static portfolios of securities, liquidating the positions and cashing out investors after a finite holding period that typically lasts a few years.Olden Lane’s debut vehicle, currently under review by the SEC, would have a three-year life. It would invest in S&P 500 options with the aim of protecting investor capital against drops in the index of up to 20% while maintaining exposure to the market’s upside. Thus if the market rose by 20% during the fund’s lifetime, shareholders would receive their initial capital plus a 20% cumulative return. If the market fell by 20%, investors at least would be guaranteed to get their principal back. Only if the S&P 500 dropped by more than 20% would investors lose money.A key feature of the unit investment trust structure is low trading and administrative costs, since the portfolios aren’t actively managed. Investors in the planned Olden Lane vehicle, for example, would pay fees equal to roughly 0.7% of assets over the lifetime of the fund.Olden Lane also anticipates launching commodity-focused vehicles based on strategies developed both in-house and by third-party managers, as well as private offerings that would invest in a variety of instruments including stocks, bonds and derivatives.Serieyssol is Olden Lane’s majority owner. A minority interest in the firm is held by Matthew Allain, who runs a Chatham, N.J., wealth-management firm called Leo Group.Equinox, with offices in Denver and Princeton, specializes in repackaging alternative-investment strategies for retail investors. Among its offerings is a first-of-its-kind mutual fund that takes a multi-strategy approach to managed futures.Serieyssol left Equinox in September 2014. His resume also includes stints at EIM Securities, Morgan Stanley and Societe General.


















